                .row.text-justified
                    .col-md-6
                        p.text-muted
                            | The OGC API - Tiles standard describes how mapping clients (e.g: web pages, desktop applications) can get information about tilesets and how to request the tiled data itself. 
                            | It basically adds a some formality to what people have been doing for years with XYZ tilesets, while adding support for more complex use cases.
                        p.text-muted As other OGC APIs, the standard is organised in a serious of building blocks, which are mapped to conformance classes. 
                            | One may choose to conform to one or more conformance classes, according to the complexity of the use case and the aimed degree of interoperability.
                    .col-md-6
                        p.text-muted
                            | The core conformance class boils down to three simple requirements, which capture what most of the web map applications are already doing:
                        .text-left
                            ul
                                li
                                    p.text-muted Tiles must be available using a URL following a template like:
                                        code https://somehost.com/tiles/{z}/{x}/{y}.png
                                li
                                    p.text-muted Successful responses must return an http response with a 200 status code.
                                li
                                    p.text-muted If the requested tile is out-of range, a 400 or 404 status codes should be returned (204, in the case of empty tiles).
                .row.text-justified
                    .col-md-6
                        p.text-muted
                            | If you choose to also confom to “OGC API - Common - Part 1: Core”, then the {z}, {x} and {y} parameters need to be renamed to {tileMatrix} and {tileCol}.
